<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><TimeML><TIMEX3 tid="t0" functionInDocument="CREATION_TIME"/>Japanese Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata on <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX3>  <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">criticized</EVENT> controversial remarks by a powerbroker and his main supporter,  Ichiro Ozawa, about women and a major newspaper.&#13;
"It's not appropriate," the prime minister <EVENT eid="e2" class="REPORTING" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">told</EVENT> reporters, <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PRESPART" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">referring</EVENT> to  recent <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="NONE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">remarks</EVENT> by Ozawa, co-leader of the Renewal Party, one of the major  coalition forces in the government.&#13;
On <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE">Monday</TIMEX3>, Ozawa reportedly <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">branded</EVENT> the mass-circulation Asahi Shimbun  newspaper as a "red newspaper" which practices "black journalism."&#13;
On <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE">April 16</TIMEX3>, Asahi <EVENT eid="e6" class="REPORTING" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">quoted</EVENT> Ozawa as <EVENT eid="e7" class="REPORTING" tense="PRESPART" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">saying</EVENT> at a <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="NONE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">meeting</EVENT> that "one is free  to <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="INFINITIVE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">sleep</EVENT> with the woman of one's choice." He allegedly <EVENT eid="e10" class="REPORTING" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">added</EVENT>, "It's none of  your business."&#13;
Ozawa reportedly <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">made</EVENT> the controversial remarks when he <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">spoke</EVENT> about the  formation of a parliamentary union by ruling parties.&#13;
The Social Democratic Party <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">withdrew</EVENT> from the <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="NONE" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">ruling</EVENT> coalition when other  government parties <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">formed</EVENT> the parliamentary group, called Kaishin  (Renovation), shortly before Hata <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE" tense="PAST" aspect="NONE" polarity="POS" modality="none">formed</EVENT> his cabinet on <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DATE">April 28</TIMEX3>.&#13;
